Analysis of Women Primary School Completion Rate
¶

Mengfan Zhang
¶

Introduction¶

Nowadays, as is posted by J.P. Morgan research, the probability of the global economy recession by the end of 2024 is estimated to be 35%, which is a relatively higher chance comparing with 25%, the probability by the end of 2023. Therefore, it's more and more important to figure out ways to promote economic growth. The increase of female primary school completion rate is one of them. As defined by DataBank, female primary school completion rate is the population of girls that newly entering the last grade of primary school divided by the population of girls of their same age. This indicator doesn't count repeaters or those who drop from the last grade, but it's enough for us to take a look into how much the ratio of female primary school completion has changed over years and other factors. As mentioned in the webpage of Millenium Challenge Corporation, it's proven that there exists strong positive correlation between female primary school completion rate and promoted economic growth.

This is a tutorial to walk through the lifecycle of data science. The main parts of the lifecycle includes:

  • Data collection
  • Data processing
  • Exploratory analysis and data visualization
  • Analysis, hypothesis testing and Machine Learning
  • Insight and policy decision

Importing libraries¶

Before we start collecting data, we need to import the required libraries, which enables us apply pre-written functions and saves our time. Usually in a whole data science lifecycle, this part does not need to be completed at first since we always realize the lack of library after a runtime error of unknown operation is reported. However, as a tutorial, this part appears in the first place.

In [790]:
import numpy as np                                 # library for operations on large amount of data
import pandas as pd                                # library for operations on dataframes

from statsmodels.formula.api import ols            # library for assessing how much linear models fit correspnding data

Numpy and pandas are fundamental libraries in a data science lifecycle. They both deal with huge amount of data, but numpy focus on the mathematical operations of every element in the data structure, while pandas focus more on the changing of shape and size of dataframes. Matplotlib is a powerful library which plot the data, as its name tells. Therefore, it's crucial to data visualization. The OLS API provides us with values from a lot of aspects, such as R-squared value and p-value, the former one tells how much variance is explained by the model built, and the latter one tells how much the coefficients are fitting the scatters.

Data Collection¶

This part is simply collecting data. In this tutorial, we need 5 tables, which I've already included in the Git folder.

From my perspective, the female primary completion rate might be correlated to three variables, so I list them as features, they are the total primary completion rate, female primary school enrollment, and GDP per capita. The first one I select as feature is because if the total rate is high, it generally indicates strong educational infrastructure, policies, and cultural support for education, benefiting girls as well. The second one I select as a feature is for the reason thatmore girls enrolling in primary school increases the pool of potential completers. The third one is also a feature to the target, the reason for choosing GDP per capita is not so direct as the first two features. Countries with higher GDP per capita are with better economical conditions, so they can build more schools, improve transportation, and ensure safe environments for girls, encouraging attendance and completion.

Besides, I also include a table of nations, in order to divide different countries into groups of their corresponding regions and income groups.

In all, there are The five required tables are:

  • Primary completion rate, female (% of relevant age group) (the target, abbreviated as womed)
  • Primary completion rate, total (% of relevant age group) (one feature, abbreviated as alled)
  • School enrollment, primary, female (% gross) (one feature, abbreviated as womse)
  • GDP per capita, PPP (current international $) (one feature, abbreviated as gdppc)
  • countries (a helper table to provide evidence for classifying different countries, either by region or by income group, abbreviated as ctry)

Since the data has not been merged into one dataframe, I add a prefix "data_" to all the abbreviations mentioned above.
All tables are got from Comma-Separated Values (csv) files, pandas already contains a function called "read_csv" to convert from csv files to dataframes.
The following are the first row of each table. I use the "skiprows" to skip the headers of all tables, otherwise the csv reader will confuse how many columns to read and convert as a dataframe since each header only include 2 columns, the strings "Data Source" and "World Development Indicators", which are not we mainly study in this tutorial.

Only reserve those rows with full values of GDP per capita. I make this decision because there are various reason for the missing values of GDP per capita. For example, Syria has not reported GDP per capita from 1990 to 2016, and no data reported since 2022 as well. During these years, Syria was deeply involved in wars. Therefore, for the ideal convenience, I choose not to consider these countries with null values of GDP per capita in any year between 1990 and 2023.

Now there are still 187 rows in the "female primary completion rate" table contain null values. For this case, imputation with regressors regarding to GDP per capita as the univariate are not what we want. Even with decision tree which produces the highest coefficient of determination (score), the predicted values for imputation are exploding to over 400. Instead, we need a nearby value, so I use ffill to fill the empty space with the nearest available year.
Another reason for applying $ffill$ but not $bfill$ is that I assume that one reason of why a country refuses to update any value might be that the newest value is almost the same as the current value but the latter value cannot be inferred as the value in the previous year because no one can reasonably infer what happened in the previous year.

After that, I use melt to change the rows and columns of each dataframe.

Melt is a function to rearrange the dataframe. Each row is with IDs of a variable and different values of the variable.
In this case, I set the IDs as "Country Code", "Region", "IncomeGroup" and "Indicator Name", and the variables are those data from 1990 to 2023. After that, the data can be transformed to such a shape that the values each year for every country is in a single column. The convenience of this operation is shown shortly after this block.

Another function apply right after "melt" is "rename" since we cannot leave those columns as "variable" and "value" for every dataframe, otherwise "variable" and "value" are anbiguous. You can easily notice that I didn't drop the column "Indicator Name" but I also didn't mention its necessity. This point is where it is needed. I replace the column name "value" with the indicator name of each dataframe. Since the indicator name for every observation is the same in a dataframe, I only extract the first entry of the column "Indicator Name" to replace the column name "value". The name to replace "variable" is simply yearID. The "rename" function is also applied to all dataframes except dataframe of countries.

In [828]:
data_womed.rename(columns={"variable": "yearID", "value": data_womed.loc[0,'Indicator Name']}, inplace = True)

data_gdppc.rename(columns={"variable": "yearID", "value": data_gdppc.loc[0,'Indicator Name']}, inplace = True)
data_womse.rename(columns={"variable": "yearID", "value": data_womse.loc[0,'Indicator Name']}, inplace = True)

Analysis, hypothesis testing and machine learning¶

The first step of hypothesis testing is to raise hypotheses, in other words, guesses. I made two guesses before I build models to the data.

The first guess is that primary completion rate is related to the region.

As the above scatter plots and OLS result summaries indicate, the linear model can only predict the pattern between female primary school enrollment and female primary school completion rate within groups "Low Income" and "Lower Middle Income", so it's not very correlated with female primary school completion rate.

Analysis, hypothesis testing and Machine Learning¶

As GDP per capita and the total primary completion rate predict the most when the countries are divided by their income groups, when building the model, I consider to divide all the countries by income groups instead of region and include GDP per capita and the total primary completion rate as features. This time I still choose to predict the future data using linear model, since using the machine learning regressors sometimes gives me skyrocketing results such as 600%, which is unrealistic. To avoid this, I prefer linear regression.

Among all the features, GDP per capita and total primary school completion rate can be taken to build a linear model to predict the future female primary school completion rate. Therefore, I treat them as features, and female primary school completion rate as the target.

In [864]:
# select wanted columns
model_df = df.loc[df['IncomeGroup'] != '-'].groupby(["IncomeGroup","yearID"])\
                                                [['GDP per capita, PPP (current international $)',\
                                                  'Primary completion rate, total (% of relevant age group)',\
                                                  'Primary completion rate, female (% of relevant age group)']].aggregate("mean")

# features
X = model_df[['GDP per capita, PPP (current international $)','Primary completion rate, total (% of relevant age group)']]
# target
y = model_df['Primary completion rate, female (% of relevant age group)']

# build the regression model
regr = LinearRegression()
# fit the model
regr = regr.fit(X,y)

# print the score
print(regr.score(X,y))
# print the coefficients
print(regr.coef_)
# print the intercept, i.e., bias
print(regr.intercept_)
